Note that 
 \begin {align*}  D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P || Q) &= \mathbb {E}_P \left [\log \left (\frac {P(x)}{Q(x)}\right )\right ] \\ &= \mathbb {E}_P \left [-\log \left (\frac {Q(x)}{P(x)}\right )\right ] \\ \end {align*} 
By Jensen's Inequality,
   \begin {align*}     D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P || Q) &\geq  -\log  \left (\mathbb {E}_P \left [\frac {Q(x)}{P(x)}\right ]\right ) = 0   \end {align*}

Define p_i = \frac {a_i}{A}, q_i = \frac {b_i}{B}, then 
 \begin {align*}   D_{\mathrm {KL}}(p || q) &= \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {B a_i}{A b_i}} \\   &= \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} - \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {A}{B}} \\   &= \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} - \log {\frac {A}{B}} \\ \end {align*} 
By Gibb's inequality,
 \begin {align*}   \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} - \log {\frac {A}{B}} \geq  0   &\implies    \sum  \frac {a_i}{A} \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} \geq  \log {\frac {A}{B}} \\   &\iff    A \sum  a_i \log {\frac {a_i}{b_i}} \geq  A \log {\frac {A}{B}} \end {align*} 
as desired.

    Recall that
     \begin {align*}       P_{e}(g) &= \sum _{x}\sum _y P_{XY}(x, y) \cdot  \mathbf {1}_{x \neq  g(y)} \\       &= \sum _{y} P_Y(y) \sum _{x} P_{X|Y}(x|y) \mathbf {1}_{x \neq  g(y)} \\       &= \sum _{y} P_Y(y) (1 - P_{X|Y}(g(y)|y)) \\     \end {align*} 
To minimize this, we take
   \begin {align*}     g^*(y) = \arg \max _{x} P_{X|Y}(x | y)   \end {align*} 
as desired.

    By Chebyshev's Inequality,
         \begin {align*}       \mathbb {P}(|\hat {X} - \mu | > a) \leq  -\frac {\sigma ^2}{a^2}     \end {align*}     
    Since X_i's are independent, 
\mathrm {Var}[\hat {X}] = \frac {1}{n^2} \sum _{i = 1}^{n} \mathrm {Var}[X_i]
    Therefore,
     \begin {align*}       \lim _{n \to  \infty } \mathbb {P}(|\hat {X} - \mu | > a) \leq  \lim _{n \to  \infty }-\frac {\sigma ^2}{n a^2} \to  0     \end {align*}

fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
Let \{X_{n}:n\geq 1\} denote i.i.d. \mathcal {X}-valued r.v. with distribution P_{X}. Then,

 \begin {align*}  \lim _{n\to \infty }-\frac {1}{n}\log  p_{X^{n}}(X_{1},\ldots ,X_{n}) &= \lim _{n \to  \infty } -\frac {1}{n} \log  \prod _{i = 1}^{n} P_X(X_i) \\  &= \mathbb {E}_{X \sim  p_X}[-\log  p_X(X)] \\   &= H(X) \end {align*} 
Equivalently, for large n
   \begin {align*}     \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon    \end {align*} 
with high probability.

Fix an \epsilon >0. Then, an \epsilon -typical set with respect to the pmf p_{X}, denoted by A_{\epsilon }^{(n)}, is defined as
\left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  \left |-\frac {1}{n} \log  p_{X^n}(X^n) - H(X)\right | \leq  \epsilon  \right \}
Alternatively,
A_{\epsilon ^{(n)}} = \left \{X^n \in  \mathcal {X}^n \mid  2^{-n(H(X) + \epsilon )} \leq  p_{X^n}(X^n) \leq  2^{-n(H(X) - \epsilon )}\right \}

For the other direction, suppose we have some R achievable. By definition, for all \epsilon  > 0, for all sufficiently large n there exists a Coding system with parameters (n, \theta ) such that
         \begin {align*}           \frac {\log  \theta }{n} < R + \epsilon , \quad  \mathbb {P}(\text {error}) < \epsilon          \end {align*}       
      Use Fano's Inequality to show this is not possible.

A randomized hypothesis test is a channel which takes in the data X and outputs a \{0,1\} valued random variable Z , where Z=i represents that the test declares that H_{i} is true, for i\in \{0,1\} .
X\sim P\longrightarrow \boxed {P_{Z|X}}\longrightarrow Z In some cases, it is sufficient to focus on non-randomized or deterministic tests, for which P_{\mathbb {Z}|X=x} is a delta function. That is, for a given realization of X , the output of the test is deterministic (it is equal to H_{0} or H_{1} with probability 1). Such deterministic tests can be equivalently represented by a function \Psi , or a subset B of the domain X :
\Psi (X)=\mathbf {1}_{B}(X)=\begin {cases}1,&\text {if}X\in B\\ 0,&\text {if}X\not \in B.\end {cases}

Consider a hypothesis testing problem with observations  X^{n}\stackrel {\text {i.i.d.}}{\sim }P_{X} , with the null  H_{0} : P_{X} =P_{0}  and alternative  H_{1}:P_{X}=P_{1} . Then, the optimal NP test with level  \alpha \in  (0,1]  has the following structure:

 \Psi _{NP}^{*}(X^{n})=\begin {cases}1,&\text { if }L(X^{n})>\tau \\ \gamma ,&\text { if }L(X^{n})=\tau \\ 0,&\text { if }L(X^{n})<\tau .\end {cases} 

In the above display,  L(X^{n})  denotes the likelihood ratio  p_{1}(X^{n})/p_{0}(X^{n}) , and  \gamma \in [0,1]  and  \tau \geq 0  are constants that ensure  \pi _{1|0}(\Psi ^*_{NP})=\mathbb {P}_{H_{0}}(\Psi ^*_{NP}(X^{n})=1)=\alpha  . Namely, 
\tau  = \inf \{\tau  \mid  \alpha  \geq  \mathbb {P}(L(X^n) > \tau )\} and \gamma  = \frac {\alpha  - \mathbb {P}(L(X^n) > \tau )}{\mathbb {P}(L(X^n) = \tau )}

Let \mathcal {X} denote an alphabet of size m , and let \mathcal {P}=\{P_{1},\ldots ,P_{k}\} denote a collection of k distinct distributions on \mathcal {X} (every P_{i} can be identified with a pmf in \Delta _{m} ). Now, consider the following two-player game:
Player 1, representing adversary, chooses a distribution P from the set \mathcal {P}
Player 2, representing source coder, constructs a code according to the distribution Q \in \Delta _m without knowledge of P The goal of Player 2is to identify a Q that minimizes the worst-case redundancy {\mathcal {R}}^{*}\equiv {\mathcal {R}}^{*}({\mathcal {P}}):=\operatorname *{min}_{Q\in \Delta _{m}}\operatorname *{max}_{P\in {\mathcal {P}}}{\mathcal {R}}(P,Q)=\operatorname *{min}_{Q\in \Delta _{m}}\operatorname *{max}_{P\in {\mathcal {P}}}D_{\mathrm {KL}}(P\parallel Q).

A class of subsets \mathscr {F} of \Omega  is a \sigma -field if the following holds

\Omega  \in  \mathscr {F}

If A \in  \mathscr {F} then A^c \in  \mathscr {F}

If A_1, A_2, \ldots  \in  \mathscr {F} then \bigcup _{i = 1}^{\infty } A_i \in  \mathscr {F}

A set function is a real-valued function defined on some class of subsets of \Omega . A set function P on a field \mathscr {F} is a probability measure if it satisfies these conditions:


0\leq  P(A)\leq 1 for A\in \mathscr {F};

P(\varnothing )=0, P(\Omega )=1;

if A_{1},A_{2},\ldots  is a disjoint sequence of \mathscr {F} sets and if \bigcup _{k=1}^{\infty }A_{k}\in \mathscr {F}, then P\Big (\bigcup _{k=1}^{\infty }A_{k}\Big )=\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }P(A_{k}).

A class \mathscr {L} is a \lambda -system if it contains \Omega  and is closed under the formation of complements and of finite and countable disjoint unions:


\Omega \in \mathscr {L};


A\in \mathscr {L} implies A^{c}\in \mathscr {L};


A_{1},A_{2},\ldots ,\in \mathscr {L} and A_{n}\cap  A_{m}=\varnothing  for m\neq  n imply \bigcup _{n}A_{n}\in \mathscr {L}.

A class \mathscr {M} of subsets of \Omega  is monotone if it is closed under the formation of monotone unions and intersections:


A_{1},A_{2},\ldots \in \mathscr {M} and A_{n}\uparrow  A imply A\in \mathscr {M};

A_{1},A_{2},\ \ldots \in \mathscr {M} and A_{n}\downarrow  A imply A\in \mathscr {M}.

Let (\Omega , \mathscr {F}, P) be an arbitrary probability space, and let X be a real-valued function on \Omega . X is a simple random variable if it has finite range and if 
\left [\omega  \mid  X(\omega ) = x \right ] \in  \mathscr {F}
for each x in its finite range.

